Right now, we do not have the ability to make prompt users when entering tags and commands.

To support this functionality, we add a Trie data structure to handle fetching of autocorrected text.

This allows users to be guided through the commands in early use.

Right now, we cannot take notes on people in the Address Book, which some users may want to do.

To fix this, we add a new class Note to add a note field to the person model, as well as NoteCommand and NoteCommandParser to handle the new note command. Finally, we edit our other classes to support the operations required to process, track and save notes.

This allows users to put down a simple note for each of the people in the Address Book, to further identify them.

We do not require the address field in newly created person objects, since professors do not need to keep track of their mentees' addresses.

Fix code style issues.

commitResults.messageTitle: Add User Stories and Use Cases to Developer Guide
Refactor: Refactor Command Parsing and Execution
commitResults.messageBody:
Right now, we use a very simple command system, where each command has its own Parser and Command class, and there is no inheritance or OOP within these. This is not sufficient as we want to implement subcommands to our applications based on the Objects we will create.

To support this functionality, we add an Executor with the current Model instance to allow the execution of commands to be separated from the classes. We also create the TargetedCommand, GroupCommand and PersonCommand classes that are more specific versions of the Command class.

This allows us to specify the target of the command after parsing the first command word. We can then do the remaining parsing and execution afterwards.

3 classes need to be added for each new person Command: a class that extends `PersonCommandParser`, a class that extends `PersonExecutor` and a class that extends `PersonCommand`.

Fix javadocs.
Fix bugs.

TODO: Make sure that all person/group specific commands follow the correct format.
This reverts commit 45bbb72b2a9297325928ae867d3506b3b4a98422.

Presently, the command parser is still parsing using the default AB3 command structure, which severely limits what we can do with our features.

To fix this, we switch the parser to use our new command structure.

Notable bugs:
* SubCommand related parsers, commands and executors do not work yet
* NotorParser does not seem to identify arguments correctly

Currently, our Trie implementation only supports finding the first item or the first item based on a query. This is insufficient if we are to use it for our Trie command.

Therefore, we add the findAllMatches command to return us a list of all the matches in our Trie.

This allows us to easily display whole lists filtered by a search string.

Right now, users may have all their contacts shown on screen, which can get very cluttered after a long time. There lacks a method to safely remove these people from Notor yet preserve them for future reference.

To solve this, we add the archive and unarchive commands. This allows users to move unaccessed users into the archive portion of the application. The unarchive command also serves as a way to show all archived users when deciding who to reinstate to Notor.

This keeps users that are less contacted out of the way and frees up space in Notor. Unarchive command allows users to bring select users back into Notor if they decide that these users need to be contacted frequently again.
